gap_minder <-gapminder %>% 
  select(year, continent, gdpPercap) %>%
  group_by(year,continent) %>%
  summarise_if(is.numeric, funs(min,max),na.rm = TRUE)

  • Look at the spread of GDP per capita across countries within the continents.
gap_spread <-gapminder %>%
  select(year, continent, gdpPercap)

ggplot(gap_spread, aes(x=continent, y=gdpPercap))+
  geom_boxplot(fill = "skyblue", color = "blue")+
  labs(x = "Continent", y = "GDP per Capita") +
  ggtitle("Spread of GDP per Capita Across Continents") +
  theme_minimal()

  • How does life expectancy vary across different continents?
gap_life <-gapminder %>%
  select(continent,year,lifeExp)%>%
  group_by(year, continent)%>%
summarise(mean_life = mean(lifeExp),na.rm = TRUE)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
glimpse(gap_life)

ggplot(gap_life, aes(x = year, y = mean_life, color = continent)) +

  labs(x = "Year", y = "Mean life expectancy") +

  theme_minimal()

  • Report the absolute and/or relative abundance of countries with low life expectancy over time by continent: Compute some measure of worldwide life expectancy - you decide - a mean or median or some other quantile or perhaps your current age. Then determine how many countries on each continent have a life expectancy less than this benchmark, for each year.

Absolute Number of Countries Below Mean Life Expectancy by Continent

Table

gap_data <-gapminder %>%
  select(country,continent,year,lifeExp)
glimpse(gap_data)
## Rows: 1,704
## Columns: 4
## $ country   <fct> "Afghanistan", "Afghanistan", "Afghanistan", "Afghanistan", …
## $ continent <fct> Asia, Asia, Asia, Asia, Asia, Asia, Asia, Asia, Asia, Asia, …
## $ year      <int> 1952, 1957, 1962, 1967, 1972, 1977, 1982, 1987, 1992, 1997, …
## $ lifeExp   <dbl> 28.801, 30.332, 31.997, 34.020, 36.088, 38.438, 39.854, 40.8…
mean_life_expectancy <- mean(gap_data$lifeExp, na.rm = TRUE)
countries_below_benchmark <- gap_data %>%
  group_by(year, continent) %>%
  summarise(countries_below_benchmark = sum(lifeExp < mean_life_expectancy, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Companion Graph

ggplot(countries_below_benchmark, aes(x = year, y = countries_below_benchmark, color = continent)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Number of Countries Below Benchmark") +
  ggtitle("Absolute Number of Countries Below Mean Life Expectancy by Continent") +
  theme_minimal()

Description/Writeup

Among all continents, Africa has the highest number of countries with life expectancy below the mean of worldwide over time. Oceania has the lowest number of countries with life expectancy below the mean of worldwide over time.

Absolute Number of Countries Below 50 years life expectancy by Continent

Table

life_below_50 <- gap_data %>%
  group_by(year, continent) %>%
  summarise(life_below_50 = sum(lifeExp < 50, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Companion Graph

ggplot(life_below_50, aes(x = year, y = life_below_50, color = continent)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Number of Countries Below 50 years life expectancy") +
  ggtitle("Absolute Number of Countries Below 50 years life expectancy by Continent") +
  theme_minimal()

Description/Writeup

Over time, there has been a notable decline in the number of countries in Africa, the Americas, and Asia with life expectancy below 50 years. Conversely, in Europe and Oceania, there has been little significant change in the number of countries with life expectancy below 50 years.
